{{nihongo|'''''Bubblegum Crisis'''''|バブルガムクライシス|Baburugamu Kuraishisu|lead=yes}} is a 1987 to 1991 [[cyberpunk]] [[original video animation]] (OVA) series produced by [[Youmex]] and animated by [[Anime International Company|AIC]] and [[Artmic]].<ref name="IGN">{{Citation|title=Cannes 09: Bubblegum Crisis: The Movie - IGN|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2009/05/14/cannes-09-bubblegum-crisis-the-movie|language=en|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> The series was planned to run for 13 episodes, but was cut short to just 8.

The series involves the adventures of the Knight Sabers, an all-female group of [[mercenaries]] who don [[powered exoskeleton]]s and fight numerous problems, most frequently rogue robots. The success of the series spawned [[#Spin-offs|several sequel series.]]

==Plot==
{{See also|List of Bubblegum Crisis characters}}

The series begins in late 2032, seven years after the Second Great Kanto earthquake has split [[Tokyo]] geographically and culturally in two. During the first episode, disparities in wealth are shown to be more pronounced than in previous periods in post-war Japan. The main adversary is Genom, a [[megacorporation]] with immense power and global influence. Its main product are [[Boomer (Bubblegum Crisis)|boomers]]—artificial cybernetic life forms that are usually in the form of humans, with most of their bodies being machine; also known as "cyberoids". While Boomers are intended to serve mankind, they become deadly instruments in the hands of ruthless individuals. The AD Police are tasked to deal with Boomer-related crimes. One of the series' themes is the inability of the department to deal with threats due to political infighting, [[red tape]], and an insufficient budget.

==Setting==
The setting displays strong influences from the movies ''[[Blade Runner]]'' and ''[[Streets of Fire]]''.<ref name="Animerica2">{{Cite web|url=http://www.animerica-mag.com/features/10.12/bubblegumcrisis.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040212053530/http://www.animerica-mag.com/features/10.12/bubblegumcrisis.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2004-02-12|title=Animerica: Animerica Feature: Bubblegum Crisis|date=2004-02-12|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref><ref name="FilmMonthly">{{Cite web|url=http://www.filmmonthly.com/video_and_dvd/bubblegum_crisis_retrospective_part_i_1.html|title=Film Monthly.com – Bubblegum Crisis Retrospective: Part I|website=www.filmmonthly.com|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> The opening sequence of episode 1 is modeled on the opening sequence of ''Streets of Fire''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://teleport-city.com/2014/06/02/streets-of-fire/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-04-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905062027/http://teleport-city.com/2014/06/02/streets-of-fire/ |archive-date=2015-09-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The humanoid robots known as "boomers" in the series also resemble Terminators cyborgs from the ''[[The Terminator|Terminator]]'' film.<ref name="FilmMonthly"/>

Suzuki explained in a 1993 ''[[Animerica]]'' interview the meaning behind the cryptic title: "We originally named the series 'bubblegum' to reflect a world in crisis, like a chewing-gum bubble that's about to burst."<ref name="interview">{{cite journal |last= Horibuchi |first= Seiji |date= May 1993 |title= The Animerica interview: Toshimichi Suzuki|url= |journal= [[Animerica]] |location= |volume= 1| number=3|publisher= }}</ref>

== Production ==
The series started with [[Toshimichi Suzuki]]'s intention to remake the 1982 film ''[[Techno Police 21C]]''.<ref name="Animerica1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.animerica-mag.com/features/bgc.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040407164515/http://www.animerica-mag.com/features/bgc.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2004-04-07|title=Animerica: Animerica Feature: Bubblegum Crisis|date=2004-04-07 |via=web.archive.org|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> However, he met [[Junji Fujita]] and the two discussed ideas, and decided to collaborate on what later became ''Bubblegum Crisis''.<ref name="Animerica1"/> [[Kenichi Sonoda]] acted as character designer, and designed the four female leads. [[Masami Ōbari]] created the mechanical designs.<ref name="Animerica1"/> Obari would also go on to direct episodes 5 and 6.

The OVA series is eight episodes long but was originally slated to run for 13 episodes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.animefringe.com/magazine/2005/12/special/06.php|title=Specials - Anime in Retrospect: Bubblegum Crisis |date=December 2005|website=Animefringe|access-date=2019-10-23}}</ref> Due to legal problems between [[Artmic]] and [[Youmex]], who jointly held the rights to the series, the series was discontinued prematurely.

