===Other shows===
* ''[[A.D. Police Files]]'' is a three-part original video animation produced by Youmex and animated by Artmic and AIC, released in 1990. It takes place in the original ''Bubblegum'' universe.
* ''[[A.D. Police: To Protect and Serve]]'' is 12-episode anime television series released in 1999 and is a sequel to ''[[A.D. Police Files]]''.
* ''[[Bubblegum Crisis Tokyo 2040]]'' is a 26-episode anime television series broadcast in 1998–1999. It is a [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]] of the original series.
* ''[[Parasite Dolls]]'' is a three-part original video animation series made in 2003 and set in the original Bubblegum universe.

===Crossover appearances===
In 1993, it appeared on ''[[Gall Force#Ten Little Gall Force & Scramble Wars|Scramble Wars]]'', a crossover event between ''Bubblegum Crisis'', ''[[Gall Force]]'', ''[[Genesis Survivor Gaiarth]]'', ''AD Police'' and ''[[Riding Bean]]''.

==Other media==
=== RPGs===

* ''[[Bubblegum Crisis (role-playing game)|Bubblegum Crisis]]'' role-playing game produced by R. Talsorian Games.[https://web.archive.org/web/20130730094444/http://www.talsorian.com/bgcindex.shtml] It introduces an alternate setting named "Bubblegum Crossfire", basing on a premise that data units with hardsuit blueprints have been sent to more individuals than just Sylia Stingray, resulting in that by 2033 there are numerous Knight Saber-like groups spread all over the globe. RTG's license to produce this game has expired and at present all copies of back stock have been sold.
:: * "Bubblegum Crisis: Before and After" (covering material from A.D. Police Files and Bubblegum Crash)
:: *"Bubblegum Crisis EX" which includes completely new materials (also incorporating early design concepts for BGC mecha and hardsuits as new variants)

===Novels===
The series' creator Toshimichi Suzuki wrote two novels:

* ''Bubblegum Crisis Vol. 1: Silent Fanfare'', Fujimi Shobo
* ''Bubblegum Crisis Vol. 2: Break Down-48'', Fujimi Shobo

=== Comic book ===
In Japan, a number of comic books were produced that featured characters and storylines based in the same universe. Some were very much thematically linked to the OVA series, while others were "one-shots" or comedy features. A number of artists participated in the creation of these comics, including [[Kenichi Sonoda]], who had produced the original Knight Saber character designs. A North American comic based in the Bubblegum Crisis Universe was published in [[English language|English]] by [[Dark Horse Comics]].

* ''Go! Go! Sabers!'', a comic by Tokio Kazuka.
* ''Soldier Blue'', a comic by Toshimichi Suzuki. It serves as a prequel to Bubblegum Crash! It was also made as an audio drama. It was translated into English language in 1997 by R.Talsorian Games. [http://www.jhedge.com/sldrblue/index.htm A copy of the translated dialogue can be found here].
* ''Bubblegum Crisis: Grand Mal'' produced by [[Adam Warren (comics)|Adam Warren]] via [[Dark Horse Comics]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.darkhorse.com/Comics/93-212/Bubblegum-Crisis-Grand-Mal-1-of-4|title=Bubblegum Crisis: Grand Mal #1 (of 4) :: Profile :: Dark Horse Comics|website=www.darkhorse.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite newsgroup|author=trebor |newsgroup=alt.fan.bgcrisis|title=Mason Largo Theory Part 2 [WAS Re: [INFO&#93; ANOTHER BUBBLEGUMCRISIS FAQ (Part 3/3)&#93;|message-id=8jbo8c$d7e$1@nnrp1.deja.com
| url=https://groups.google.com/forum/#!original/alt.fan.bgcrisis/nSyPvPd79GU/B4CFTVpgDUEJ|date=2000-06-28 |accessdate=2009-05-15}}</ref>

=== Video games ===
* ''Crime Wave'': a game for [[PC-88]], set in Megatokyo and featuring Knight Sabers as the main characters.<ref>[http://www.anime-games.co.uk/bgc98.php]</ref>
* ''Bubblegum Crash'': a game for [[TurboGrafx-16]].<ref>[http://www.anime-games.co.uk/bubcrashpce.php]</ref>

===Live-action movie===
In May 2009 it was announced that a [[live-action]] movie of "Bubblegum Crisis" was in the early stages of production. A production agreement was signed at the 2009 [[Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name="IGN"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/entertainment/view/429391/1/.html |title=channelnewsasia.com |publisher=channelnewsasia.com |date=2008-11-13 |accessdate=2009-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2008-11-24/aic-agrees-to-live-action-bubblegum-crisis-proposal |title=AIC Agrees to Live-Action Bubblegum Crisis Proposal (Updated) |work=Anime News Network |date=2009-05-11 |accessdate=2009-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2008-11-25/pre-production-bubblegum-crisis-film-remake-image-posted |title=Pre-Production Bubblegum Crisis Film Image Posted |work=Anime News Network |date=2009-05-11 |accessdate=2009-05-15}}</ref> The film was expected to be released in late 2012 with a budget of 30 million.<ref name="IGN"/> The production staff was said to have consulted with the original anime's staff members, [[Shinji Aramaki]] and [[Kenichi Sonoda]], to help maintain consistency with the world of the original.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-05-14/2012-bubblegum-crisis-film-planned-with-caucasisan/asian-cast|title=2012 Bubblegum Crisis Film Planned with Caucasian/Asian Cast (Updated)|date=2009-05-14|publisher=Anime News Network|work=News|accessdate=2009-07-05}}</ref> However, no further developments have been announced.

